#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:5
msgid "Good Integration Practices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:8
msgid "Install package with pip"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:10
msgid ""
"For development, we recommend you use :mod:`venv` for virtual environments "
"and :doc:`pip:index` for installing your application and any dependencies, "
"as well as the ``pytest`` package itself. This ensures your code and "
"dependencies are isolated from your system Python installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:15
msgid ""
"Create a ``pyproject.toml`` file in the root of your repository as described "
"in :doc:`packaging:tutorials/packaging-projects`. The first few lines should "
"look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:19
msgid ""
"[build-system]\n"
"requires = [\"hatchling\"]\n"
"build-backend = \"hatchling.build\"\n"
"\n"
"[project]\n"
"name = \"PACKAGENAME\"\n"
"version = \"PACKAGEVERSION\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:29
msgid ""
"where ``PACKAGENAME`` and ``PACKAGEVERSION`` are the name and version of "
"your package respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:31
msgid ""
"You can then install your package in \"editable\" mode by running from the "
"same directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:33
msgid "pip install -e ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:37
msgid ""
"which lets you change your source code (both tests and application) and "
"rerun tests at will."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:43
msgid "Conventions for Python test discovery"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:45
msgid "``pytest`` implements the following standard test discovery:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:47
msgid ""
"If no arguments are specified then collection starts from :confval:"
"`testpaths` (if configured) or the current directory. Alternatively, command "
"line arguments can be used in any combination of directories, file names or "
"node ids."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:50
msgid "Recurse into directories, unless they match :confval:`norecursedirs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:51
msgid ""
"In those directories, search for ``test_*.py`` or ``*_test.py`` files, "
"imported by their `test package name`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:52
msgid "From those files, collect test items:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:54
msgid "``test`` prefixed test functions or methods outside of class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:55
msgid ""
"``test`` prefixed test functions or methods inside ``Test`` prefixed test "
"classes (without an ``__init__`` method). Methods decorated with "
"``@staticmethod`` and ``@classmethods`` are also considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:57
msgid ""
"For examples of how to customize your test discovery :doc:`/example/"
"pythoncollection`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:59
msgid ""
"Within Python modules, ``pytest`` also discovers tests using the standard :"
"ref:`unittest.TestCase <unittest.TestCase>` subclassing technique."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:66
msgid "Choosing a test layout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:68
msgid "``pytest`` supports two common test layouts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:71
msgid "Tests outside application code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:73
msgid ""
"Putting tests into an extra directory outside your actual application code "
"might be useful if you have many functional tests or for other reasons want "
"to keep tests separate from actual application code (often a good idea):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:77
msgid ""
"pyproject.toml\n"
"src/\n"
"    mypkg/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        app.py\n"
"        view.py\n"
"tests/\n"
"    test_app.py\n"
"    test_view.py\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:90
msgid "This has the following benefits:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:92
msgid ""
"Your tests can run against an installed version after executing ``pip "
"install .``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:93
msgid ""
"Your tests can run against the local copy with an editable install after "
"executing ``pip install --editable .``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:95
msgid ""
"For new projects, we recommend to use ``importlib`` :ref:`import mode "
"<import-modes>` (see which-import-mode_ for a detailed explanation). To this "
"end, add the following to your configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:99
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = [\"--import-mode=importlib\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:107
msgid ""
"Generally, but especially if you use the default import mode ``prepend``, it "
"is **strongly** suggested to use a ``src`` layout. Here, your application "
"root package resides in a sub-directory of your root, i.e. ``src/mypkg/`` "
"instead of ``mypkg``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:112
msgid ""
"This layout prevents a lot of common pitfalls and has many benefits, which "
"are better explained in this excellent `blog post`_ by Ionel Cristian Mărieș."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:119
msgid ""
"If you do not use an editable install and use the ``src`` layout as above "
"you need to extend the Python's search path for module files to execute the "
"tests against the local copy directly. You can do it in an ad-hoc manner by "
"setting the ``PYTHONPATH`` environment variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:123
msgid "PYTHONPATH=src pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:127
msgid ""
"or in a permanent manner by using the :confval:`pythonpath` configuration "
"variable and adding the following to your configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:132
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"pythonpath = [\"src\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:139
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"pythonpath = src"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:146
msgid ""
"If you do not use an editable install and not use the ``src`` layout "
"(``mypkg`` directly in the root directory) you can rely on the fact that "
"Python by default puts the current directory in ``sys.path`` to import your "
"package and run ``python -m pytest`` to execute the tests against the local "
"copy directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:150
msgid ""
"See :ref:`pytest vs python -m pytest` for more information about the "
"difference between calling ``pytest`` and ``python -m pytest``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:154
msgid "Tests as part of application code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:156
msgid ""
"Inlining test directories into your application package is useful if you "
"have direct relation between tests and application modules and want to "
"distribute them along with your application:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:160
msgid ""
"pyproject.toml\n"
"[src/]mypkg/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    app.py\n"
"    view.py\n"
"    tests/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_app.py\n"
"        test_view.py\n"
"        ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:173
msgid ""
"In this scheme, it is easy to run your tests using the :option:`--pyargs` "
"option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:175
msgid "pytest --pyargs mypkg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:179
msgid ""
"``pytest`` will discover where ``mypkg`` is installed and collect tests from "
"there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:181
msgid ""
"Note that this layout also works in conjunction with the ``src`` layout "
"mentioned in the previous section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:186
msgid ""
"You can use namespace packages (PEP420) for your application but pytest will "
"still perform `test package name`_ discovery based on the presence of "
"``__init__.py`` files.  If you use one of the two recommended file system "
"layouts above but leave away the ``__init__.py`` files from your "
"directories, it should just work.  From \"inlined tests\", however, you will "
"need to use absolute imports for getting at your application code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:198
msgid ""
"In ``prepend`` and ``append`` import-modes, if pytest finds a ``\"a/b/"
"test_module.py\"`` test file while recursing into the filesystem it "
"determines the import name as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:202
msgid ""
"determine ``basedir``: this is the first \"upward\" (towards the root) "
"directory not containing an ``__init__.py``.  If e.g. both ``a`` and ``b`` "
"contain an ``__init__.py`` file then the parent directory of ``a`` will "
"become the ``basedir``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:207
msgid ""
"perform ``sys.path.insert(0, basedir)`` to make the test module importable "
"under the fully qualified import name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:210
msgid ""
"``import a.b.test_module`` where the path is determined by converting path "
"separators ``/`` into \".\" characters.  This means you must follow the "
"convention of having directory and file names map directly to the import "
"names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:215
msgid ""
"The reason for this somewhat evolved importing technique is that in larger "
"projects multiple test modules might import from each other and thus "
"deriving a canonical import name helps to avoid surprises such as a test "
"module getting imported twice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:220
msgid ""
"With :option:`--import-mode=importlib` things are less convoluted because "
"pytest doesn't need to change ``sys.path``, making things much less "
"surprising."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:228
msgid "Choosing an import mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:230
msgid ""
"For historical reasons, pytest defaults to the ``prepend`` :ref:`import mode "
"<import-modes>` instead of the ``importlib`` import mode we recommend for "
"new projects. The reason lies in the way the ``prepend`` mode works:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:234
msgid ""
"Since there are no packages to derive a full package name from, ``pytest`` "
"will import your test files as *top-level* modules. The test files in the "
"first example (:ref:`src layout <src-layout>`) would be imported as "
"``test_app`` and ``test_view`` top-level modules by adding ``tests/`` to "
"``sys.path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:239
msgid ""
"This results in a drawback compared to the import mode ``importlib``: your "
"test files must have **unique names**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:242
msgid ""
"If you need to have test modules with the same name, as a workaround you "
"might add ``__init__.py`` files to your ``tests`` folder and subfolders, "
"changing them to packages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:246
msgid ""
"pyproject.toml\n"
"mypkg/\n"
"    ...\n"
"tests/\n"
"    __init__.py\n"
"    foo/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py\n"
"    bar/\n"
"        __init__.py\n"
"        test_view.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:260
msgid ""
"Now pytest will load the modules as ``tests.foo.test_view`` and ``tests.bar."
"test_view``, allowing you to have modules with the same name. But now this "
"introduces a subtle problem: in order to load the test modules from the "
"``tests`` directory, pytest prepends the root of the repository to ``sys."
"path``, which adds the side-effect that now ``mypkg`` is also importable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:267
msgid ""
"This is problematic if you are using a tool like tox_ to test your package "
"in a virtual environment, because you want to test the *installed* version "
"of your package, not the local code from the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:271
msgid ""
"The ``importlib`` import mode does not have any of the drawbacks above, "
"because ``sys.path`` is not changed when importing test modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:280
msgid "tox"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:282
msgid ""
"Once you are done with your work and want to make sure that your actual "
"package passes all tests you may want to look into :doc:`tox <tox:index>`, "
"the virtualenv test automation tool. ``tox`` helps you to setup virtualenv "
"environments with pre-defined dependencies and then executing a pre-"
"configured test command with options.  It will run tests against the "
"installed package and not against your source code checkout, helping to "
"detect packaging glitches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:292
msgid "Do not run via setuptools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:294
msgid ""
"Integration with setuptools is **not recommended**, i.e. you should not be "
"using ``python setup.py test`` or ``pytest-runner``, and may stop working in "
"the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:298
msgid ""
"This is deprecated since it depends on deprecated features of setuptools and "
"relies on features that break security mechanisms in pip. For example "
"'setup_requires' and 'tests_require' bypass ``pip --require-hashes``. For "
"more information and migration instructions, see the `pytest-runner notice "
"<https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-runner#deprecation-notice>`_. See also "
"`pypa/setuptools#1684 <https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/issues/1684>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:305
msgid ""
"setuptools intends to `remove the test command <https://github.com/pypa/"
"setuptools/issues/931>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:309
msgid "Checking with flake8-pytest-style"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:311
msgid ""
"In order to ensure that pytest is being used correctly in your project, it "
"can be helpful to use the `flake8-pytest-style <https://github.com/m-burst/"
"flake8-pytest-style>`_ flake8 plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:314
msgid ""
"flake8-pytest-style checks for common mistakes and coding style violations "
"in pytest code, such as incorrect use of fixtures, test function names, and "
"markers. By using this plugin, you can catch these errors early in the "
"development process and ensure that your pytest code is consistent and easy "
"to maintain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:319
msgid ""
"A list of the lints detected by flake8-pytest-style can be found on its "
"`PyPI page <https://pypi.org/project/flake8-pytest-style/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:323
msgid ""
"flake8-pytest-style is not an official pytest project. Some of the rules "
"enforce certain style choices, such as using `@pytest.fixture()` over "
"`@pytest.fixture`, but you can configure the plugin to fit your preferred "
"style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:328
msgid "Using pytest's strict mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:332
msgid ""
"Pytest contains a set of configuration options that make it more strict. The "
"options are off by default for compatibility or other reasons, but you "
"should enable them if you can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:336
msgid ""
"You can enable all of the strictness options at once by setting the :confval:"
"`strict` configuration option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:340
#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:347
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"strict = true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:352
msgid ""
"See the :confval:`strict` documentation for the options it enables and their "
"effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:354
msgid ""
"If pytest adds new strictness options in the future, they will also be "
"enabled in strict mode. Therefore, you should only enable strict mode if you "
"use a pinned/locked version of pytest, or if you want to proactively adopt "
"new strictness options as they are added. If you don't want to automatically "
"pick up new options, you can enable options individually:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:361
#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:371
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"strict_config = true\n"
"strict_markers = true\n"
"strict_parametrization_ids = true\n"
"strict_xfail = true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:379
msgid ""
"If you want to use strict mode but having trouble with a specific option, "
"you can turn it off individually:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:383
#: ../../../doc/en/explanation/goodpractices.rst:391
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"strict = true\n"
"strict_parametrization_ids = false"
msgstr ""
